Definition 3.19. We define the homotopy category $\mathsf{HoGph}$ by modding out the 2-cells in the 2-category $\mathsf{Gph}$.. The objects of $\mathsf{HoGph}$ are the same as the objects of $\mathsf{Gph}$, and the arrows of $\mathsf{HoGph}$ are given by equivalence classes $[f]$ of graph morphisms, where $f$ and $g$ are equivalent if they have a 2-cell between them, that is, if they are homotopic. This also defines a natural projection functor $\Psi:\mathsf{Gph}\to\mathsf{HoGph}$.
Definition 2.1. The category of graphs $\mathsf{Gph}$ is defined by: • An object is a graph $G$, consisting of a set of vertices $V(G)=\{v_{i}\}$ and a set $E(G)$ of edges connecting them, where each edge is given by an unordered set of two vertices. If two vertices are connected by an edge, we will use notation $v_{1}\underline{\phantom{w}}v_{2}\in E(G)$, or just $v_{1}\underline{\phantom{w}}v_{2}$ if the parent graph is clear. • An arrow in the category $\mathsf{Gph}$ is a graph morphism $f:G\to H$. Specifically, this is given by a set map $f:V(G)\to V(H)$ such that if $v_{1}\underline{\phantom{w}}v_{2}\in E(G)$ then $f(v_{1})\underline{\phantom{w}}f(v_{2})\in E(H)$.
Definition 4.1. Let $f,g:G\to H$ be graph morphisms. We say that $f$ and $g$ are a spider pair if there is a single vertex of $G$, say $x$, such that $f(y)=g(y)$ for all $y\neq x$. If $x$ is unlooped there are no additional conditions, but if $x\underline{\phantom{w}}x\in E(G)$, then we require that $f(x)\underline{\phantom{w}}g(x)\in E(H)$. When we replace $f$ with $g$ we refer to it as a spider move.
Definition 2.12. A walk in $G$ of length $n$ is a morphism $\alpha:P_{n}\to G$. A looped walk in $G$ of length $n$ is a morphism $\alpha:I_{n}^{\ell}\to G$. If $\alpha(v_{1})=x$ and $\alpha(v_{n})=y$ we say $\alpha$ is a walk [resp. looped walk] from $x$ to $y$.
Definition 4.12. A graph $G$ is homotopy minimal if it is not homotopy equivalent to any proper subgraph of itself.
Definition 3.9 (Composition of Homotopies). Suppose that $f,f^{\prime}:G\to H$ and $g,g^{\prime}:H\to K$. Given $\alpha:f\simeq f^{\prime}$ and $\beta:g\simeq g^{\prime}$, we define $\alpha\circ\beta$ from $gf$ to $g^{\prime}f^{\prime}$ as follows: let $g\alpha=g_{*}\alpha$ denote the homotopy from $gf$ to $gf^{\prime}$, and $(f^{\prime})^{*}\beta=\beta f^{\prime}$ denote the homotopy from $gf^{\prime}$ to $g^{\prime}f^{\prime}$, as defined in Lemma 3.5. Then $\alpha\circ\beta=g\alpha*\beta f^{\prime}.$
Definition 6.4. Let $\alpha=(v_{0}v_{1}v_{2}\dots v_{n})$ be a walk in $G$. We say that $\alpha$ is prunable if $v_{i}=v_{i+2}$ for some $i$. In this case, we call the walk $\alpha^{\prime}$ obtained by deleting the vertices $v_{i}$ and $v_{i+1}$ from the walk the prune of $\alpha$: If $\alpha=(v_{0}v_{1}v_{2}\dots v_{i-1}v_{i}v_{i+1}v_{i}v_{i+3}\dots v_{n})$ then the prune of $\alpha$ is $\alpha^{\prime}=(v_{0}v_{1}v_{2}\dots v_{i-1}v_{i}v_{i+3}\dots v_{n})$
Definition 3.1. [6] Given $f,g:G\to H$, we say that $f$ is homotopic to $g$, written $f\simeq g$, if there is a map $\Lambda:G\times I_{n}^{\ell}\to H$ such that $\Lambda|_{G\times\{0\}}=f$ and $\Lambda|_{G\times\{n\}}=g$. We will say $\Lambda$ is a length $n$ homotopy.
Definition 4.7. If $G$ is a graph, we say that a morphism $f:G\to G$ is a fold if $f$ and the identity map are a spider pair.
Definition 2.2. [10, 16] The (categorical) product graph $G\times H$ is defined by: • A vertex is a pair $(v,w)$ where $v\in V(G)$ and $w\in V(H)$. • An edge is defined by $(v_{1},w_{1})\underline{\phantom{w}}(v_{2},w_{2})\in E(G\times H)$ for $v_{1}\underline{\phantom{w}}v_{2}\in E(G)$ and $w_{1}\underline{\phantom{w}}w_{2}\in E(H)$.
Definition 3.12. Two homotopies $\alpha,\alpha^{\prime}$ from $f$ to $g$ are themselves homotopic if they are homotopic rel endpoints viewed as looped walks in $(H^{G})^{I_{n}^{\ell}}$.
Definition 6.2. Let $\mathfrak{W}G$ be the walk graph formed by taking the colimit over the $\Delta^{*}$ inclusions above. Because $\Delta$ preserves parity, we have two components for this graph, formed by $(X^{P_{0}})^{\ell}\hookrightarrow(X^{P_{2}})^{\ell}\hookrightarrow(X^{P_{4}})^% {\ell}\hookrightarrow(X^{P_{6}})^{\ell}X\hookrightarrow\dots$ and $(X^{P_{1}})^{\ell}\hookrightarrow(X^{P_{3}})^{\ell}\hookrightarrow(X^{P_{5}})^% {\ell}\hookrightarrow\dots$ where the $\ell$ denotes the looped subgraph of the exponential object representing the walks. An object in this colimit will be represented by some finite length $n$ walk $\alpha=(v_{0}v_{1}v_{2}\dots v_{n-1}v_{n})$ such that this walk is identified in the colimit with the length $n+2$ walk $\Delta^{*}(\alpha)=(v_{0}v_{1}v_{2}\dots v_{n-1}v_{n}v_{n-1}v_{n})$.
Definition 4.2. We will denote by ${\bf ZComp}$ the full subcategory of the category ${\bf Comp}$ whose objects are all Hausdorff compactifications $c:X\longrightarrow Y$ for which $Y$ is a zero-dimensional space.
Definition 3.6. Let $C\in|\mbox{{\boldmath$Caba$}}|$ and $A,B$ be Boolean subalgebras of $C$. If for every $a\in A$ and any $x\in\mbox{{\rm At}}(C)$ such that $x\leq a$ there exists $b\in B$ with $x\leq b\leq a$, then we will say that $A$ is t-coarser than $B$ in $C$ or that $B$ is t-finer than $A$ in $C$; in this case we will write $A\preceq_{C}B$. We will say that the Boolean algebras $A$ and $B$ are t-equal in $C$ if $A\preceq_{C}B$ and $B\preceq_{C}A$.
Definition 2.3. Let $(X,\tau)$ be a zero-dimensional Hausdorff space. A Boolean algebra $A$ is called admissible for $(X,\tau)$ (or, a Boolean base for $(X,\tau)$) if $A$ is a Boolean subalgebra of the Boolean algebra $\mbox{{\rm CO}}(X)$ and $A$ is an open base for $(X,\tau)$. The set of all admissible Boolean algebras for $(X,\tau)$ will be denoted by ${\cal B}{\cal A}(X,\tau).$
Definition 2.2. An extension of a space $X$ is a pair $(Y,c)$, where $Y$ is a space and $c:X\longrightarrow Y$ is a dense embedding of $X$ into $Y$. Two extensions $(Y_{i},c_{i}),\ i=1,2$, of $X$ are called isomorphic (or equivalent) if there exists a homeomorphism $\varphi:Y_{1}\longrightarrow Y_{2}$ such that $\varphi\circ c_{1}=c_{2}$. Clearly, the relation of isomorphism is an equivalence in the class of all extensions of $X$; the equivalence class of an extension $(Y,c)$ of $X$ will be denoted by $[(Y,c)].$ We write $(Y_{1},c_{1})\leq(Y_{2},c_{2})$ and say that the extension $(Y_{2},c_{2})$ is larger than the extension $(Y_{1},c_{1})$ if there exists a continuous mapping $\varphi:Y_{2}\longrightarrow Y_{1}$ such that $\varphi\circ c_{2}=c_{1}$. This relation is a preorder (i.e., it is reflexive and transitive). In the class of all Hausdorff extensions of $X$, the equivalence relation associated with this preorder (i.e., $(Y_{1},c_{1})$ is larger than $(Y_{2},c_{2})$ and conversely) coincide with the relation of isomorphism defined above. Setting for every two Hausdorff extensions $(Y_{i},c_{i}),\ i=1,2$, of a Hausdorff space $X$, $[(Y_{1},c_{1})]\leq[(Y_{2},c_{2})]\mbox{ iff }(Y_{1},c_{1})\leq(Y_{2},c_{2}),$ we obtain a well-defined relation on the set of all, up to equivalence, Hausdorff extensions of $X$; it is already an order.
Definition 3.16. Let $A$ be a Boolean algebra and $B\in|\mbox{{\boldmath$Caba$}}|$. A Boolean monomorphism $\alpha:A\longrightarrow B$ is said to be a Boolean z-map (briefly, z-map) if every atom of $B$ is a meet of some elements of $\alpha(A)$. A z-map $\alpha:A\longrightarrow B$ is called a maximal Boolean z-map (briefly, mz-map) if for every Boolean subalgebra $C$ of $B$ which is t-equal to $\alpha(A)$ in $B$, we have that $C\subseteq\alpha(A)$.
Definition 3.1. A pair $(A,X)$, where $A$ is a Boolean algebra and $X\subseteq{\bf Bool}(A,\mbox{{\bf 2}})$, is called a Boolean z-algebra (briefly, z-algebra; abbreviated as ZA) if for each $a\in A^{+}$ there exists $x\in X$ such that $x(a)=1$.
Definition 3.8. A z-algebra $(A,X)$ is called a Boolean dz-algebra (briefly, dz-algebra; abbreviated as DZA) if it satisfies the following condition: (Dw) If $B$ is a Boolean subalgebra of $(P(X),\subseteq)$ and $B$ is t-equal to $s_{A}^{X}(A)$ in $(P(X),\subseteq)$, then $B\subseteq s_{A}^{X}(A)$.
Definition 2.14. The action functor $T\colon\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\mathcal{D}$ satisfies the projection formula if the natural morphism $X\otimes T^{R}(V)\longrightarrow T^{R}(T(X)\otimes V)$ is an isomorphism for every $X\in\mathcal{C}$ and $V\in\mathcal{D}$.
Definition 3.7. Let $\mu\colon\mathcal{F}\rightarrow A$ be a quantum moment map. The Hamiltonian reduction of $A$ is the $k$-algebra $\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{D}}(1,A\otimes_{\mathcal{F}}1).$
